<body>

  <div class="container">
    <h1>Tech Looks Pretty. It Isn’t</h1>
    <div class="subtitle">A reality check from inside the chaos</div>

    <p>
      If you’ve ever looked at a clean UI, a smooth app, or a “simple” website and thought,
      <span class="highlight">“wow, that’s neat”</span> — just know that behind that neatness is chaos.
    </p>

    <p>
      Not the dramatic kind. The quiet kind. The kind that lives in console errors, broken dependencies,
      and code that worked yesterday but refuses to cooperate today.
    </p>

    <h2>The Beautiful Lie of Simplicity</h2>

    <p>Tech products look effortless on the surface.</p>

    <ul>
      <li>A button clicks</li>
      <li>A page loads</li>
      <li>A feature works</li>
    </ul>

    <p>But behind that?</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Multiple layers of logic</li>
      <li>APIs talking to other APIs</li>
      <li>Databases storing and retrieving data</li>
      <li>Edge cases nobody warned you about</li>
      <li>At least one “temporary fix” that became permanent</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      What users see is <span class="highlight">design</span>.  
      What developers deal with is <span class="highlight">systems</span>.
    </p>

    <div class="quote">
      And systems are rarely aesthetic.
    </div>

    <h2>The Reality: It’s Confusing (for Everyone)</h2>

    <p>
      One thing nobody tells you early enough:
      <span class="highlight">feeling lost in tech is normal.</span>
    </p>

    <p>
      You’ll open documentation and understand nothing.  
      You’ll try tutorials that don’t work exactly like shown.  
      You’ll Google the same error 17 times.
    </p>

    <p>
      And sometimes… you’ll fix something without knowing how.
    </p>

    <div class="quote">
      That’s not failure. That’s literally the process.
    </div>

    <h2>I’m still figuring things out...but here’s what’s helping me stay sane:</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Focusing on learning, not perfection</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Accepting confusion as part of growth</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Building anyway</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Keeping things practical</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>For Anyone Lost in This Tech Multiverse</h2>

    <p>If you’re new or confused,you’re not behind.</p>

    <h3>1. Learn Version Control Early</h3>
    <p>
      Start using <span class="highlight">Git and GitHub</span>.  
      It helps you track changes, collaborate, and not destroy your own code accidentally.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Don’t Just Watch — Build</h3>
    <p>Building messy things teaches more than perfect tutorials ever will.</p>

    <h3>3. Break Things</h3>
    <p>Debugging is a skill. The more things break, the better you get.</p>

    <h3>4. You Don’t Need to Know Everything</h3>
    <p>You just need to know how to figure things out.</p>

    <h3>5. Keep It Sustainable</h3>
    <p>Consistency beats intensity. Burnout helps no one.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Final Thought</h2>

    <p>
      Tech isn’t just about clean code and beautiful interfaces.It’s about navigating complexity and staying curious.
    </p>

    <p>
      Some days it feels exciting.Some days it feels overwhelming.
    </p>

    <div class="quote">
      But if you keep showing up, it starts making sense! not all at once, but enough to keep going.
    </div>

    <div class="footer">
      © 2026 Hasinova · Built with confusion, curiosity, and a lot of debugging
    </div>
  </div>

